# Link Underline Consistency Rule

## Overview
Always apply the `link-underline` utility class to non-button `<a>` elements to maintain consistent animated underline behavior throughout the project.

## When to Apply
- **Apply to**: All `<a>` elements that are navigation links, content links, or interactive text links
- **Do NOT apply to**: Button elements, social media icons, or decorative links that shouldn't have underlines

## Implementation
```html
<!-- ✅ Correct: Navigation and content links -->
<a href="/about" class="link-underline">About Us</a>
<a href="/contact" class="link-underline font-black uppercase">Contact</a>
<a href="/blog" class="link-underline text-brand-red">Read More</a>

<!-- ✅ Correct: Links with other hover effects -->
<a href="/work" class="link-underline transition-all hover:translate-x-[-2px] hover:translate-y-[-2px]">
  View Work
</a>

<!-- ❌ Don't apply to: Button-style elements -->
<button class="btn-primary">Submit</button>

<!-- ❌ Don't apply to: Social media icons -->
<a href="https://linkedin.com" class="social-icon">
  <svg>...</svg>
</a>
```

## CSS Implementation
The `link-underline` utility is defined in `packages/core/src/styles/bracketbear.tailwind.css`:

```css
@layer components {
  .link-underline {
    position: relative;
  }
  .link-underline::after {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    bottom: -0.25em;
    width: 0;
    height: 0.2em;
    background-color: currentColor;
    transition: width 0.3s cubic-bezier(0.4,0,0.2,1);
    z-index: 1;
  }
  .link-underline:hover::after,
  .link-underline:focus-visible::after {
    width: 100%;
  }
}
```

## Guidelines
1. **Always add `link-underline`** when creating new navigation or content links
2. **Preserve existing styling** - the utility works alongside other classes
3. **Use semantic judgment** - if it's a clickable text link, it should probably have the underline
4. **Test on hover** - ensure the animation feels smooth and appropriate for the context

## Examples by Context
- **Navigation menus**: Always apply
- **Footer links**: Always apply  
- **Content links** (blog posts, articles): Always apply
- **Call-to-action links**: Usually apply (unless they're button-styled)
- **Social media links**: Usually don't apply (they're icon-based)
- **Logo/brand links**: Usually don't apply (they're branding elements)
